"Lioubimtseva E., Cole R., Adams J.M., Kapustin G.","Impacts of climate and land-cover changes in arid lands of Central Asia",2005,"Journal of Arid Environments","62","2",,"285","308",,,10.1016/j.jaridenv.2004.11.005,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-17644380672&partnerID=40&md5=9ee00c627e622198fb40eb3ed35394e2","Geography and Planning Department, Grand Valley State University, 1150 AuSable Hall, Allendale, MI 49401, United States; Biology Department, Rutgers University, United States; Geography Institute, Russian Academy of Science, Russian Federation","Lioubimtseva, E., Geography and Planning Department, Grand Valley State University, 1150 AuSable Hall, Allendale, MI 49401, United States; Cole, R., Geography and Planning Department, Grand Valley State University, 1150 AuSable Hall, Allendale, MI 49401, United States; Adams, J.M., Biology Department, Rutgers University, United States; Kapustin, G., Geography Institute, Russian Academy of Science, Russian Federation","Despite the growing understanding of the global climate change, great uncertainties exist in the prediction of responses of arid regions to global and regional, natural and human-induced climate change. Meteorological data series show a steady increase of annual and winter temperatures in Central Asia since the beginning of the 20th century that might have a strong potential impact on the region's natural ecosystems, agricultural crops, and human health. Analyses of the NOAA AVHRR temporal series since the 1980s showed a decrease in aridity from 1991-2000 compared to 1982-1990. While most climate models agree that the temperature in arid Central Asia will increase by 1-2°C by 2030-2050, precipitation projections vary from one model to another and projected changes in the aridity index for different model runs show no consistent trend for this region. Local and regional human impacts in arid zones can significantly modify surface albedo, as well as water exchange and nutrient cycles that could have impacts on the climatic system both at the regional and global scales. © 2005 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Central Asia; Climate change; Desert; Land cover; Land use","arid region; AVHRR; climate change; climate modeling; land cover; land use; NOAA satellite; Asia; Central Asia; Eastern Hemisphere; Eurasia; World",,,,,,"Batjes, N.H., Sombroeck, W.G., Possibilities for carbon sequestration in tropical and subtropical soils (1997) Global Change Biology, 3, pp. 161-173; Bazilevich, N.I., (1995) Biomass and Biologic Production of Vegetation Formations of the Former USSR (Biomassa I Bioproductivnost Rastitelnih Formatsij), , Nauka Moscow; Berger, A.L., Long-term variations of caloric solar radiation resulting from the Earth's orbital elements (1978) Quaternary Research, 9, pp. 139-167; Chub, V.E., (2000) Climate Change and Its Impact on the Natural Resources Potential of the Republic of Uzbekistan. (Izmenenija Klimata I Ego Vlijanije Na Prirodno-Resursnij Potensial Respubliki Uzbekistan), , Gimet Tashkent; Chichasov, (1990) Hydrometeorological Problems of the Aral Sea Area (Gidrometeorologicheskije Problemi Priaralya), , Gidrometeoizdat Leningrad; Claussen, M., Brovkin, V., Ganopolski, A., Kubatzki, C., Petoukhov, V., Climate change in northern Africa: The past is not the future (2003) Climate Change, 57, pp. 99-118; Doluhanov, P.M., Aridnaja zona Straogo Sveta v pozdnem pleistosene I holocene (Arid zone of the Old World in the Late Pleistocene and Holocene) (1985) Bulletin of the All-Russian Geographic Society, 117 (1), pp. 16-23; Diem, J., Brown, D.P., Anthropogenic impacts on summer precipitation in Central Arizona, USA (2003) Professional Geographer, 55 (33), pp. 343-356; (2004) FAO Agricultural Data, , http://apps.fao.org/, United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization, Rome; Glantz, M., (1999) Creeping Environmental Problems and Sustainable Development in the Aral Sea Basin, , Cambridge University Press Cambridge; Glazovskaja, M.A., (1996) 